Quick Start: Implementing the Governance Layer
A practical checklist for getting from "files in the repo" to "running governance layer." Designed to be worked through in order over a few weeks.

Week 1: Foundation

 Copy this entire governance/ folder into the repository root.
 Update the repository's top-level README.md to link to governance/README.md prominently — under a heading like "Cultural Authority and Consent" placed before the technical module documentation.
 Replace the existing bare ethics-and-consent-principles file with a redirect note pointing to governance/. (Better: delete it and link from the README.)
 Add the four Local Contexts Notice icons to the top-level README, displayed prominently. Download icons from localcontexts.org/labels/notices. Do not modify the icons.

Week 2: Hub registration

 Decide which entity registers on the Local Contexts Hub. Options: Pulau Brani Project as an institution; Nuramira as researcher; Singapore Heritage Society as institution. The Hub asks who holds the relationship with the community.
 Register at localcontextshub.org.
 Create the first Project on the Hub representing the toolkit as a whole.
 Generate the four Notices (TK, BC, Attribution Incomplete, Open to Collaborate) on the Hub.
 Copy the Hub Project URI into governance/README.md and into the metadata schema's local_contexts.hub_project_uri default.
 Display the Notices on the Pulau Brani Project website and the GitHub repository's main README, each linking to its Hub URI.

Week 3: Pilot catalog entries

 Identify three pilot items — ideally one oral history, one photograph, and one dialect entry — already collected with strong consent.
 For each, complete a copy of catalog_entry_template.md, fully filled in, applying at minimum the TK Notice and any other relevant Notices.
 Pair each pilot entry with a completed CONSENT_AGREEMENT_TEMPLATE.md. Store consent records in a restricted-access location (not in the public Git repo).
 Have a small community circle review the three pilot entries. Note what was easy, what was hard, what wording confused people, what needs to be added.
 Revise the templates based on this feedback before scaling.

Month 2: Community Label co-creation

 Convene a community workshop dedicated to Labels. Walk through LOCAL_CONTEXTS_LABELS_REFERENCE.md together. Use the Local Contexts Labels Adapt Activity packet as a facilitation guide.
 Identify which Labels the community wishes to customise. Likely first candidates: TK Community Voice (TK CV), TK Attribution (TK A), TK Culturally Sensitive (TK CS), TK Non-Commercial (TK NC), TK Outreach (TK O). Sacred/restricted Labels (TK SS, TK WR, TK MR) come up as needed; the community decides when.
 Draft customised title text and template text for each Label, including translations into local Malay. Get community sign-off through whatever decision-making process the community has chosen.
 Apply the customised Labels on the Hub. The Hub generates a Label URI for each — copy this back into catalog entries.

Month 3 onward: Operationalise

 Build the metadata schema into whatever storage layer the Community Archive uses (database, file store, CMS). Mukurtu CMS has native TK Label support and may be worth evaluating; if building custom, mirror the schema in METADATA_SCHEMA.md exactly.
 Implement the validation rules listed at the bottom of METADATA_SCHEMA.md as enforced checks at ingest time. Items missing a Notice should not be saved.
 Implement the AI-processing filter. Every module that ingests catalog items (Memory Constellation Engine, Ask Pulau Brani, Memory Map) reads the access.tier and access.ai_processing fields and excludes accordingly. The filter is the contract.
 Build the consent withdrawal flow. A contributor emails the revocation contact; an item is moved to a withdrawn tier within thirty days; downstream indexes are rebuilt to honour the withdrawal.
 Add a public-facing "How we handle cultural materials" page on the Pulau Brani Project website that explains the framework in plain language and links to the governance folder.


A note on Mukurtu
Mukurtu CMS is an open-source content management system built specifically for community-controlled archives, with TK Labels integrated natively. Before building all of this in custom code, it is worth running a serious evaluation of whether Mukurtu can host the Community Archive module. If so, the toolkit becomes the layer that sits above Mukurtu — adding the AI Heritage Lab, Memory Constellation Engine, Ask Pulau Brani, Advocacy tools — while Mukurtu handles the cataloging foundation. This would save significant build time and inherit a community of practice.
If Mukurtu is the choice, this governance folder remains useful as the human-readable specification and policy layer that sits above the platform.

Common pitfalls to avoid

Applying Labels without community authority. Notices are yours to apply; Labels are not. If a Label appears in a catalog entry without a Hub Label URI and a named community authoriser, something has gone wrong.
Stripping Notices and Labels during export. The whole point is that protocols travel with the data. Any pipeline that exports without preserving the local_contexts field is broken.
Treating consent as a one-time signature. Consent is a relationship. Re-visit it when new uses, new partners, or new AI features are introduced.
Letting AI systems see restricted material "just for indexing." The filter must run before embedding, not after retrieval. Vectors of sacred material in an index are still a leak.
Modifying the Label icons. They are recognised internationally precisely because they look the same everywhere. Use them as published.


Where to ask for help

Local Contexts team: support@localcontexts.org. They run free informational sessions and Hub demos.
Mukurtu community: forums on mukurtu.org.
CARE Principles guidance: Global Indigenous Data Alliance, gida-global.org.
